For each element, the number of ways it can be included in the sequence is independent across elements. For each element, the choices are: not included in any subset, or included starting from the first subset \( A_i \) and remaining in all subsequent subsets. This gives 11 choices per element (from never included to included starting at \( A_1 \) up to \( A_{10} \)). Therefore, the total number of sequences is \( 11^{10} \). However, we need the sum of the number of sequences for each \( n \) from 1 to 10. For each \( n \), the number of sequences is \( (n+1)^{10} \). Thus, we need to compute: \[ K = \sum_{n=1}^{10} (n+1)^{10} \] This sum modulo 10 is calculated by finding each term modulo 10 and summing the results: \[ \begin{aligned} 2^{10} &\equiv 4 \mod 10, \\ 3^{10} &\equiv 9 \mod 10, \\ 4^{10} &\equiv 6 \mod 10, \\ 5^{10} &\equiv 5 \mod 10, \\ 6^{10} &\equiv 6 \mod 10, \\ 7^{10} &\equiv 9 \mod 10, \\ 8^{10} &\equiv 4 \mod 10, \\ 9^{10} &\equiv 1 \mod 10, \\ 10^{10} &\equiv 0 \mod 10, \\ 11^{10} &\equiv 1 \mod 10. \end{aligned} \] Summing these results: \[ 4 + 9 + 6 + 5 + 6 + 9 + 4 + 1 + 0 + 1 = 45 \] Finally, \( 45 \mod 10 = 5 \). Thus, the remainder when \( K \) is divided by 10 is \(\boxed{5}\).
